{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b8e5a3ef-d260-4968-afee-cb6c5051f215","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe project itself is clean — the bottleneck is **MSBuild cold-start overhead** on every `dotnet build` invocation. Each CLI call spawns a new process, JITs MSBuild, and re-evaluates the project graph before discovering nothing changed. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping MSBuild loaded in-process.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**1. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop** — keeps the build host warm and rebuilds on file changes, eliminating startup cost entirely:\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n# or for run+rebuild:\ndotnet watch run\n```\n\n**2. Enable the MSBuild build server** (opt-in on .NET 8, default in .NET 9+) — reuses a long-lived MSBuild process across CLI invocations:\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build   # first build warms the server; subsequent builds are fast\n```\n\n**3. Upgrade to .NET 9+** — the build server is enabled by default, and the terminal logger (`--tl`) is on, both of which reduce CLI build latency. You'd update the csproj:\n```xml\n<TargetFramework>net9.0</TargetFramework>\n```\n\n### Why this works\n\n| Approach | Startup cost | Project eval | Compile (no-op) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `dotnet build` (cold) | ~1-2s JIT | ~0.5-1s | <0.5s |\n| `dotnet build` (build server) | ~0s (reused) | ~0.1s (cached) | <0.5s |\n| `dotnet watch` | ~0s (persistent) | ~0s (watched) | <0.5s |\n\nThe **fastest path** for edit-build-test cycles is `dotnet watch`. For ad-hoc builds, setting `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` closes most of the gap with Visual Studio.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bf3463cd-39de-4a0f-8454-b3135ef05ffe","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even with no changes), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. They've already verified analyzers aren't the issue and that incremental build targets work correctly.\n\nThe root cause is clear: every `dotnet build` invocation starts a new MSBuild process, parses the project files, evaluates the project graph, and then determines nothing needs to be built. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping MSBuild loaded in-process with a persistent \"design-time build\" server.\n\nThe key solution is to use the **MSBuild Server** (also known as the build server or `dotnet build-server`). \n\nStarting with .NET 8, MSBuild supports a persistent server process that persists across builds, mirroring how Visual Studio keeps MSBuild warm. The main approach is enabling the MSBuild build server by setting the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` environment variable or using the `--tl` flag, which implicitly activates the server—this is enabled by default in .NET 9+ but requires opt-in for .NET 8. For development workflows, `dotnet watch` keeps the process alive and monitors for file changes, eliminating the startup overhead entirely. For CLI work specifically, the most practical approach is using `dotnet watch` to keep the process warm during development, enabling the MSBuild build server through an environment variable (which is opt-in for .NET 8 but default in .NET 9), and considering an upgrade to .NET 9+ where these optimizations are built in. At the project level, I'm looking at whether disabling code style enforcement in the build could help, since the project itself is already fairly clean without heavy analyzers or complex dependencies.","outputTokens":1299,"requestId":"4418:BF224:16EC3E2:1A02EDC:69FE857D"},"id":"0ab0de21-989f-43b8-a9f5-fc3a37f83eaa","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:53:47.526Z","parentId":"a069a4fd-8ef3-4159-9637-13ffaa2c0d9d"}
